longest_values: Finally, we have a Saturday Arts program where students can participate in Music, Drama, and Art. This program runs from November to May, ending with a theatrical performance. The school has two culminating assemblies, once in the winter and the other in the late spring where students perform in each of their respective disciplines. Also, twice a year we have an ""ART Gallery"" display on our first floor where students showcase their visual arts pieces. The displays are received well by parents, teachers and students. Teachers in all grades have a fifteen minute dance/movement/ theater break every day."

participate in a rotating program of theatre and visual arts. The visual and theatre arts students follow the NYC Blueprint for the Arts and an alignment to the Common Core Standards. Activities in the theatre and visual arts program include but are not limited to art studio,drama club, museum club, dance performances, digital photography, winter and spring concerts, and a school-wide celebration of learning. Some of our students have been accepted into summer art intensives at Frank Sinatra School for the Arts.

Harlem Vocal Ensemble students have performed around the country and in this year's Harlem SING! We expect to complete our modern chorus facility in 2018 and further develop the program with Mr. Darius Kennebrew, Program Director. Our Visual Arts and Dance programs include 2-year sequences.  We continued our partnerships with Aquila Theater, Sports and Arts in Schools Foundation, Spanish Dance Arts and Apollo Education at https://vimeo.com/216767798

The school has a collaboration with the Disney Organization, where Disney drama educators work with students and staff so that the students may perform the show, ""The Jungle Book."" The entire school community was involved with The Jungle Book production in some capacity. The arts provide a pathway to learning that connects the common core learning standards and the NYCDOE Blueprints for the Arts as well as parent engagement."

Additionally, our Urban Arts partnership offers rigorous residency programs in a wide range of art forms, taught by expert teaching artists. All programs use a project based approach for students to develop pre-professional skills and key vocabulary while producing high quality, original artworks. Students also develop an increased awareness of career opportunities in the arts."

"Please note that the data recorded in STARS does not reflect the entirety of our arts programming.  For example, third grade does not currently receive music instruction as a cluster period.  However, students participate in the Link Up program in conjunction with Carnegie Hall, whereby they enjoy intensive orchestral music education and learn to play the recorder.  They also participate in a community-oriented Flag Day ceremony which fuses theater, dance, and music - and is the centerpiece of our civic education as PS 6.  The aforementioned is done during the music teacher's administrative period, or when the classroom teachers have availability and is not termed as ""music"" within the tracking database.  Where programming does not suit our creative/compliance needs, we accommodate accordingly.   In that vein, the dance teacher has instituted a Dance Company.  Children engage in choreography/performance for festivals and events throughout the school year.  Similarly, the visual arts teacher has formed a stagecraft club; students create set pieces for the numerous productions that we stage at PS 6.  We are pleased to offer our students an extensive artistic menu to reflect their diverse interests and capabilities."

This year was another exciting year of art for students at PS 15, as we continue to expand our programs and partners (adding Puppetry this year). In addition, through implementation of the School-wide Enrichment Model, the faculty and staff have played an integral part in providing sustainable arts programming based on student-interest in clusters such as âArt for Change,â âPhotography,â âMaking Musicâ and âTrash to Treasureâ. 
We continued residency programs with organizations such as The Children's Museum of Art, Mark DeGarmo Dance and Third Street Music, in which kindergarten through fifth grade students learned through the Orff Shulwerk approach. Students explored basic rhythms/melodies using various instruments. 
All our students visited arts museums, films and performances to supplement and extend arts learning objectives grown out of classroom curriculum. We continued our nine-year relationship with Arts for All, Inc, providing our kindergarten through second grade students with opportunities to integrate theater and visual art into literacy. Our students have many opportunities to express themselves through dance, music, and theater with our partnerships with Mark DeGarmo Dance, Rosieâs Broadway Kids, puppetry with Arts Connection and creative storytelling with Story Pirates. Lastly, through our Technology Arts class, students study mentor artists, learn coding, graphic design, and animation. We expect to have many submissions to this yearâs District 1 Arts Fair and close the year on a high note for Arts at PS 15!

We strongly believe that the arts should be an important part of a school's academic program. We have participated in and developed a wide variety of educational programs and activities to support the inclusion of the arts (music, art, movement and drama) in the daily curriculum offerings to our students. Many community agencies support us including Third Street Music School, Rosie's Broadway Kids and the Beacon after school program. Visitors to PS 19 often comment on the extent to which the students are engaged with their work. We are particularly proud of our school's warm and sociable tone and productive learning environment.

Every student at PS 20 is engaged in the arts in a variety of ways. Our current partnerships have allowed us to provide dance and movement instruction to all of our students in grades 2-5. Turtle Bay Music School continues to provide ORFF and world music classes to our students in grades PK-2 as well as a chorus for our 3rd graders. Our classroom teachers, cluster teachers, and our partners work closely to integrate the arts into our units of study. In addition to our many partnerships, we have a school based visual arts teacher and music teacher who meet with most of the classes once a week. Both arts teachers try to coordinate their curriculum with the literacy and social studies curriculum. Another partnership we are very proud of is our that with American BaLLET Theater, our 5th graders get too learn ballet and theater. The students get an opportunity to perform at the Metropolitan Opera House at the end of the year. Our Fourth graders dance all year with teachers from the National Dance Institute and have 2 performances for Families and school. In addition, our 5th graders get to be part of Rosie's Broadway Kids, this program gives them the opportunity to go to a Broadway show. They also have weekly dance classes for half of the school year. Our Art teacher and Music teacher are active all year teaching all our students to play instruments and different fine arts techniques. This year they will have a Arts festival day where they will present to the student.We are always looking for new ways to expand our programming

Students perform in a winter and spring concert. Our school partners with two community based organizations that provide visual arts and music instruction. We continue to partner with Rosie's Kids theater program.

PS 221 prides itself on arts education. Our programs include visual arts, musical, and dance instruction. Our music program includes singing, performing, Orff, recorder, guitar, ukulele, and drums. We perform in school concerts and community outreach. Our 4th grade performs a holiday concert, 3rd grade a recorder concert, & 2nd grade Earth friendly songs at our Science Fair. This year we performed for the Queensboro presidentâs office during the winter holidays. We also have group of fifth graders in our North Hills Harmonics. Our visual arts program includes 5th grade sketchbooks, art history, and a partnership with Deepdale Cares. This yearâs community project created artwork for our school atrium and their coop community. Together students and Deepdale Cares seniors worked painted terracotta pots, stepping stones, and birdhouses. We also have âArtify It!â, an art enrichment program. Our students participate in the Square 1 visual arts project. Our dance program includes Dancing Classrooms and our annual Dance Festival. Our theatre experiences included Circus Arts, Marathon Playhouse, Queens Theater, LeAP, and the Queens Museum. Our visual arts experiences included the MET. We hold an annual talent show, Family Art Night and an Open Mic event.

"We have established a solid relationship with Studio In a School and are in our eighth year of partnership. Our resident artist works diligently with every student in grades K-5. We have very strong parental involvement which is imperative to the success of the program. Studio offers professional development for classroom teachers and has implemented special projects to ""expand the frame"" linking art with other content areas. We are considered a ""STEAM"" school. Students'artwork has been displayed in such venues as The Asia Society,The Brooklyn Historical Society, Museum of the City of New York, and The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Fifth grade students were assigned a special project to create banners for Studio's 40th Anniversary Gala which were then displayed at the Seagram's Building Plaza in Manhattan. We have been awarded a Cultural After School Adventures grant through our local councilman. Through this grant, permanent artwork will be displayed for all to enjoy. Our Art Exposition is our culminating event and takes place in the middle of June for students, staff, and parents. Students in our chorus, Pre-K, and Kindergarten classes have performed several holiday shows for our student body and parents alike. All classroom teachers have participated in the NaliniKids program which encourages nurturing the whole child including physical, emotional, and character development. We have been awarded a Solar One grant which fosters a ""green"" environment. Six third-grade students participated in Ballet Tech's beginner's program."

At the Curious Young Learners Pre-K center, we believe curiosity leads the children down new paths. At the cornerstone of our school is our arts program. Children are naturally creative and derive much pleasure from involvement in the arts. They learn a host of skills and acquire tremendous self-esteem when given varied opportunities to create. Because we consider art such an integral part of our program, our children are provided with open-ended opportunities to create. Our children use a wide array of art media including acrylic, finger, and water paints, pastels, crayons, and markers. In addition, children are given the opportunity to express themselves through drawings, sculptures, models, and paintings. 
We celebrate our childrenâs creativity by prominently and artfully displaying their work throughout our preschool sweet. Because we believe the artistic process to be even more valuable than the final product, we accompany each work with a transcription of the childâs thoughts about the piece along with pictures of the process.
The children participate with increasing interest and enjoyment in a variety of music activities including listening to music, singing songs, performing finger plays and experimenting with various musical instruments. We encourage the children by creating sounds using traditional instruments like bells, drums, and recorders. Our school enrollment is approximately 97% Title 1 eligible, with disproportionately 
high representation of student groups most at risk:  47% of our students live in temporary housing (2nd highest percent across NYC public schools); 33% are classified as Students with Disabilities; 28% are English Language Learners; 66% are Latino and 32% are African American.  

The arts play a vital role in engaging our students both during the regular school day and in extended day programming, and contribute dramatically to our vibrant school culture.
A register loss has had a significant impact on our budget and has limited our ability to provide a vast array of art experiences.
2017-2018 School year will be the first school year we are building sequential arts programming. We will be offering arts tracks in dance, music, and visual arts to interested and talented students.

"Our school is committed to providing our students with a rich and diverse arts experience. This experience includes exposure to all arts disciplines, integration of art into the instructional program and exposure to all of our city's art rich cultural institutions and resources. Our students learn to appreciate art in their environment and they understand how art contributes to their lives. Our teachers are also committed to art learning through ongoing professional development offered throughout the year. They integrate visual arts into all subject areas and help students explore their creative talents in a variety of disciplines including visual arts, drama, music, dance and technology. We have great arts partnerships that help us to provide students with rich experience in all of the above. We provide music exposure and learning to all of our early childhood students and we offer instrumental music instruction in woodwinds, percussion and violin to students in third through eighth grade. Our goal moving forward is to grow our art program so that there is cumulative learning in visual arts and music in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade and to integrate theater arts into the middle school curriculum so that there is alignment to content area learning. We also seek additional funds for instruction in  visual arts on every grade.  ""Excellence, Engagement and Enrichment"" is our mission statement and we are committed to offering our students a well rounded arts experience utilizing our school and city resources."

The Arts program at Philippa Schyuler Middle School for the Gifted & Talented has been one of our prized jewels for many years! This versatile program offers students the opportunity to study a variety of disciplines. From Modern and Urban dance to Steel Pan and Concert Band, our students are immersed in learning activities that afford them the chance to express themselves and showcase their many talents in a multitude of ways. This year, one of our school's goals has been to continue to enrich and expand the Performing & Visual Arts program within our school community. 

Given this focus, we have boosted our level of performance, and expanded both of our annual winter and spring concerts to encompass more diversity and theatrical elements. We also put together an elaborate production of the theatrical play, Antigone, with full cast and crew! We have also expanded on our International Day celebrations to include more performance opportunities that highlight a variety of cultures. In addition, we have created partnerships with local Arts Educational programs to prepare our students with the foundational skills needed to succeed in these realms. Through these comprehensive programs, students learn valuable, life-long skills that are necessary to working in large and diverse groups. Additionally, they broaden the scope of our school community, allowing for teachers, students and parents to come together and acknowledge the hard work and diligence found within our Performing and Visual Arts Program.
